  "prompt": "What are the major drug targets for myeloma?",
  "response": "Here are the major drug targets for multiple myeloma:\n\n1. Proteasome Inhibitors\n- Targeting protein degradation\n- Examples: Bortezomib, Carfilzomib, Ixazomib\n\n2. Immunomodulatory Drugs (IMiDs)\n- Modulating immune system and inhibiting myeloma cell proliferation\n- Examples: Thalidomide, Lenalidomide, Pomalidomide\n\n3. Proteasome Pathway\n- Disrupting protein homeostasis\n- Targets: 26S proteasome complex\n\n4. BCL-2 Inhibitors\n- Blocking anti-apoptotic proteins\n- Example: Venetoclax\n\n5. Histone Deacetylase (HDAC) Inhibitors\n- Regulating gene expression\n- Example: Panobinostat\n\n6. Monoclonal Antibodies\n- Targeting specific surface markers\n- Examples: Daratumumab (CD38), Isatuximab (CD38)\n\n7. Signaling Pathway Inhibitors\n- Targeting key molecular pathways\n- Examples: Selinexor (XPO1 inhibitor), JAK/STAT inhibitors\n\n8. Immunotherapy\n- CAR-T cell therapies\n- Targeting B-cell maturation antigen (BCMA)\n\nThese targets aim to disrupt myeloma cell survival, proliferation, and immune interactions.",
